segments.text: before the first tape recorder failed.
I want to know how you became interested in art.
Well, I became interested in art, namely, through my mother was a wonderful artist in her own right, and I was a pencil artist, essentially, when I was a kid.
I used to study her work.
She took art in San Antonio, you know, José Opa.
became interested at that time.
I think he just had an innate feeling for it all along that I wanted to do it, but I was constantly filling notebooks and composition books with cartoons and mainly core designs.

When I was in high school, I started in grade school when I did quite a bit of scratching around with crayons and things, but, uh, and, uh, I found a kind of a soulmate or another companion, classmate that loved art too, and then Tom Steele, and we both, uh,
I started car designs and worked on the high school annual.
And I started using pen and ink as an essential medium then.
But the art, of course, it grew strong and strong all the time.
And when I finished school, I had done considerable what's called automobile designing, essentially.
I took some lessons under a lady who was in China paint.
They taught China paint, and I took some watercolor under her, and I got to feel the watercolor then.
But then there was a time, of course, when I graduated from high school to go to A&M.
It hurt my father's insistence.
I had no intention of going to A&M, because I knew it was military, and not to have a deeper version of anything as discipline and regimentation.
So I went on to A&M.
But he was certain that I'd take electrical engineering.
He had one of the Quarrel boys named Charlie Dickerson, and he had a very wonderful success, and he went to San Francisco and installed all the electrical phases of that.
I guess he did, but anyhow.
But Papa said, now there's the man.
He said, I want you to be like Charlie Dickerson, be a great engineer.
Well, there was a German.
There was strict regimentation in the German family.
It was bad enough.
Everything was mandatory.
It was suggested by the parents.
But I went to A&M.
I said, well, I'll do it.
And I did.
And I had a rugged time of it.
I got in the military.
And I was a pretty good gold brick in that.
Then I took this EE.
And I think Dr. Bolton was the head of the electrical engineering department.
But I flunked every course.
I wouldn't bring this in very forcibly.
But it was a show that how your kids are going to react.
And I ran mad.
God, I must have ran mad.
And I passed one course, and that was English under Dr. D.B.
Cofer.
And I remember he was very wonderful.
He was, you know, a genteel soul.
He said, you have a talent for writing.
And so I read all these essays and composition stories, and he read them out to the class as an example of what...
But, of course, that was just an incidental...
I think it goes hand in hand with art to some extent.
It's an emotional experience.
And I love putting down things in words.
I started, I'd say, at A&M.
But that didn't carry me through my freshman year.
because I flucked everything in.
It was nice to have.
But I did, and I don't know what the procedure was, but I was told that I didn't make my grades, and it'd be best to go ahead and retire from school.
And I was worried.
I mean, Papa found out about it.
He was awful put out with me because I couldn't pass my grades.
So I went to Dr. Brazell.
I think the registrar, Friley, told me to go see him.
So he had a nice visit with W.B.
Brazell.
And he's the one that said, well, this is a shame.
That should happen to you.
But I know you want to take a lot to him.
I want to go to Chicago and study art.
He said, well, somewhere we can work this thing out.
I'm going to call your father, which he did.
I told Papa, I said, now, listen here.
Don't go ahead and be too strict with this boy.
And artistic talents.
And Papa was, but I was sorry and everything, blah, blah.
And he went on.
So we decided what course to take.
And I said, how about architecture?
I'd been up to visit the architecture department.
I got to know some of them.
They were wonderful.
I had the department at that time named Joseph Kellogg from the University of Illinois, and they had brought him in there.
It was very genteel, wonderful.
But he gave me new inspiration and new incentive.
So I took my four years of architecture and came along.
just the opposite from what had happened in England, but I had made good grades, and I think I got some honors with it at the time.
I don't recall all these art studies.
And I finished that and got my M, a B, A in architecture.
At the same time, I was working, as I told you, on the college end.
I had 21 and 22, and they were work outs.
The art, uh, art director, whatever it is, art editor.
laying out everything, making all the color play.
If you've seen it in the 21, 22, you'll see that it wasn't a masterful work, but it was done for service.
But it took, you served all my time.
And besides that, I was rooming with part of that football team.
But I enjoyed that, too, with Bill McMillan, the quarterback.
He was the one that was on Beat Center on New Year's Day, which was wonderful.
It was his pass, and Bill McMillan, and then another All-American.
But they were all
from the University of Tennessee named Bill Bradley.
But I took as much of that as I could.
But I could not go along with this routine that was happening.
I had to get out of the room in the dormitory so I could finish my, essentially the annual work, which had to come out.
So that's when I took this place, I saw Gaslight Hall, and I went up there to see what it was like.
I saw the top story there, and I said, Lord, that would be an ideal studio.
So I roamed around up there, no creaky stairs and everything else, and I said, my God, this is it.
So I went to see Colonel Ashburn about it.
He was coming down at that time.
He said, no, I don't want you to do that.
It's a fire trap, but it's hazardous, climbing the steps, no.
I said, oh, so I just wish you could let me.
He said, well, we gave it every consideration.
But I never think nothing ever came out of it.
He didn't make a pitch of mine.
So I just said, I'm going to go on up there anyhow.
Got me some fresh fish to bring up there.
All my art materials up in my files.
This was a breeze.
I worked more than put in many, many hours, 16, 18 to 20 hours a day.
But I got the annual out and finished my other work.
But that shows what the environment and the proper circumstances can do for you, right set up.
But I fell right in line.
So I went on and participated, you say, in part of the master degree work in architecture, which I devoted to landscape architecture under Fritz Dr. Hensel.
And I had a wonderful time with him.
But I got my thesis done, everything, but again, math.
But I mean, I was looking, I got math, but I'm not a figurehead, I'm not a statistician.
So I just went ahead and got out of school.
I like about, I don't know, about four or five hours to get my math
I could have gone to summer school and rounded it out there, but I said, heck with it, I'm just going to go ahead.
I said, I've got to be A, and that's nice enough.
I went home again, started with my car designing at Tom Steele.
And Papa finally said, now listen, hey, see, I sent you to A&M.
get a reasonable education anyhow, or the semblance of it.
But he said, you've done well.
And I said, it's time for you to get out on your own.
So I went to Dallas.
Took a train.
He packed me, put me on the train with a suitcase.
And I kept going there.
I lived high off the hog with the family long enough.
And so I went to Dallas.
And I rummaged the street.
I had a time in Dallas.
I'm finding a cheap boarding house.
Stayed there.
Had no money.
And I went around and started
making the rounds of the commercial artists, essentially.
So I finally found one man that took more or less the edge of my name, John Doctoroff.
And he was a wonderful pencil artist.
He did pencil portraits.
And he did what's called average weight, saddles and shoes and everything else.
So I showed him my work.
But I won't say what exactly his terminology was.
But he looked at my drawings.
I said, man, here I am.
He'd answer, oh, my god.
I don't want to repeat that.
And he said, what are you showing me this crap for?
I said, whoa, is it that bad?
She said, you have potential.
Now if you want to come to work with me, but I cannot remunerate you.
I can't say that word, remunerate you.
And just go with me.
I think, again, I said, well, I'm just grateful for a chance to be with you and have a rub off on what you're doing.
I said, I have tremendous admiration for your work.
So she set me up with no salary, nothing.
But I subsisted on, then I did some signs, show cards, just went with this for, I think it was Grant's, it was a big store there, but on the side.
Then I posed for Wilson's, no, for the advertising, for the movie type of thing they had at that time as a model for Victor Wilson Clothes and some other drugstores.
That's the best money I ever made.
It was about $8 an hour, just posing clothes.
But nobody ever knows.
That's another bracket I got into as a model.
Now, when was this, Buck?
It was in 22 and 23.
I got, because I got out of A&M in 22, which is essentially 1923.
It was hard living, but the main thing was that I was so engrossed with what I wanted to do in my career that I went ahead.
It took anything, even for, I mean, I had a rough go of it, but I have no complaint.
It was worth it.
Did you know of the artists before you arrived in Dallas?
I knew Guy Cahoon.
There were quite a few.
He was the most reputable one in Dallas.
And I said, I'm going to aspire to get under Cahoon.
But I started to have a doctor off.
And finally I went to see Guy Cahoon, and he looked at me and said, well, I'm not ready for it yet, but I will.
And I kept on, but I did.
I took Cahoon's ads out of the paper.
He had a distinctive style in pen and ink work.
He did almost all the ads, real estate firms, and he was an architect.
And an architectural delineator, which makes it perspective.
And there's my man.
So I started in with him, and he finally took me on.
I said, I'll give you a try.
And all of a sudden, he said, my God.
I picked up his technique and everything else.
And his style, he just said, I've been looking for him.
So I went to work at $120 a week for him.
And what I did, Patrick, all of his work, I would say.
When was this, do you suppose?
I was in, I think it was 24 or something like that.
Then I finally, I just had enough of a guy came home, and he just, I pushed more and more off of him.
He just took off and made a tremendous lot of money.
So I was doing these delineations that I told you of architectural buildings, perspectives.
And I went to show that to this architectural friend of Thompson and Swain.
I said, I'm going to shoot to go for the highest.
And they were the most reputable architects in Dallas, residents, essentially residential.
They did the Highland Park home, so I showed my things to Mr. Swain, and they said, my God, we could use you in perspective ways.
Interior and everything else, I went to work and did perspectives, and I did study design under him, but it was nice, because I had a wonderful man I worked on.
Anyhow, I finally got a little bit tired of that, said, I'm going to my, see if I can go on my own.
But I had innumerable perspectives, interiors and exteriors, for all the residential and building.
Then some Houston architects came down, found out about me, and they said, come on to Houston.
It's wide open for an architectural delineator like yourself.
And so about 10 or 15 of them got me down there.
And I had a good go of it.
I went to Houston.
Incidentally, that's when I married my wife.
So I met her in Devone Reynolds.
She was in the art department.
They're handling the art supplies.
And she was essentially a very good artist in her own right.
So we went to night school at Bryan High, and then we finally decided we'd all team up and get married.
Now, this is in Dallas?
It was Dallas where this happened, yes.
It was in Dallas.
But you went to night school in Dallas at Bryan High?
Uh-huh, at Bryan.
There was an art course there, a very fine one, under a man who did the posters for Majestic Taylor.
But I learned a lot from him.
Now, of course, I continued with my wife, and she stayed on.
That's what made up our move to go to Houston.
and went down there and had a rather nice school over there.
It wasn't, but I learned.
Every time I was learning, I'd get in new places, picking up new styles, new approaches, everything, but I was out to learn.
What year did you start in A&M then?
I started in 17.
In 17.
When did you graduate from high school?
I thought you went to the Army someplace between A&M and A&M.
I went in 18, yeah.
Okay.
I went in 18.
I had to make a change.
They had, but they instigated the SATC, the Student's Army Training Corps, and we had it here.
It was on me, so I joined up here.
Had to be drafted.
And of course, went to, but we still had a course, but it was essentially a military.
But you were stationed here then on the campus itself.
Then I had a decision to make.
I went to, oh, they had different branches, truck driving, what you call it, or aviation, so I decided to go to aviation when the time came to.
I said, focus on one thing, which I did.
I passed the test.
I don't know how it ended.
So I was supposed to go to Kelly Field and go to ground school there.
And then almost to the side, it was out.
Of course, I said, well, God, why didn't I?
I should have at least got a chance to fly.
I'll go over there and get battered and run wrist-pulling.
I said, fuck it.
But, yeah, of course, almost to the side.
And I went back there, and I started all over again.
But I had a good go at A&M when I went to architecture because I did about four years of work in three years.
But I was annual.
Tammy was annual.
Where did you hear the Chicago Institute of Art?
What interested you in that?
Well, I just, now and then I run across work.
I see the ads.
But I had no, no one from Cuero had ever gone to the Institute.
There was a lot of correspondence courses.
But I was told that was the logic of some of the artists.
I mean, I don't know how in the world, but I knew that was the place at the time.
But I'm actually, I'm glad I didn't do it.
I tell you why, because if I'd have gone to that particular school, like all others, it would have been figure drawing, advertising, the same routine all of them goes through.
But then I got to architecture when I learned about buildings.
I worked on the structure.
I know what held the building together, but I learned the essentials of architecture.
And that's what stood me instead, because then I devoted to that.
And I had a field of my own.
Nobody else was there.
Only two men in Texas were doing it.
It was Cahoon and myself later.
But it opened a new door for me.
Then I went to New York, and my wife said, no, you've had enough of this.
Let's go on to New York, the headquarters, big time.
So we packed up.
Now, this is not when you leave Dallas.
No, that's when I left Houston.
How long were you in Houston?
Oh, let's see, from 26 to 20, I think, 28 years, two years in Houston.
Then you just freelanced in Houston?
I freelanced.
got a nice account from Anderson Clayton, an advertising program, 52 drawings for them, but that was essentially illustration too.
And uh... Well that's not when you did the Anderson Clayton Cotton Series, is it?
I did a Cotton Series, no, and uh, it was a fifth ad, oh I still had them here, 52.
It went, it ran in the Wall Street, 52 ads for Anderson Clayton, a whole year.
And it was a, it was a,
great thing for me because I learned about mobile drawing and about the industry itself, which stood me in good stead.
And I took on some other, a little more architecture stuff.
I got to build up a slight stockpile.
I bought us a new car and went to New York.
And that was something else too, going to New York in 1928.
Actually,
We were in dire circumstances financially, but we had to skimp and say, but keep the car and enough for gasoline and food.
So we actually ended up staying on the filling station cannabis going up to New York, selecting the car.
And I remember one incident, I might just bring it in, but we got, I think it was Wheeling, West Virginia, a big mining town.
And we got there way late.
Horrible fog, you know, it was dismal.
And it just, it just made me...
So we got onto the Philly station, went to sleep under there, and the police picked us up.
They didn't take...
I saw this text saying, what are you talking about?
God, don't you know any better than to do this?
Mining town, you could have gotten murdered or raped your wife.
So they'd come with us.
So they took me to the police, took us to the police station, and took us upstairs and gave us some cots to sleep on that night.
Next week they sent us on our way.
But I always had a lot of trouble with police force in the East.
I got on one-way streets in New Jersey and I got messed up and cussed out being a dumb Texan.
But it was, everything, to my mind, it was an exhilarating experience.
But it was fun.
I took it in that life.
Everything happens to me, always.
But the attitude of my wife, she was very good in H.H.
Buffett.
But we made it to New York.
And finally, I took about two weeks to get up there, leisurely at the same time.
That was an awesome feeling when you got over to New Jersey and got to the Dykeman Fair.
I never forget that.
I looked over at that fantastic skyline.
This is the, oh my God, we're going to barge into the same
It just looked like they were going to engulf us.
I said, well, let's get with it.
So we crossed it.
There was no place to stay.
And somebody told us about a spot on a Boston Post road or what.
We saw that in Washington, in one of the motels where we had stayed one night.
We went up there and drove that road.
We thought, oh, thank god.
We're going to find a spot to spend the night.
Then we went into this place.
I have never seen anything as filthy and dirty as that place was.
So they took us there.
They had wood stoves.
And just nothing worked, but we spent one night that we could, and then we drove on back to New York.
And we called the last resort, we called a relative of River Lee's.
He was on the Fawcett publication, George Bond.
I remember that very well.
So they said, come on over to 108th Street, where we stay in between Broadway and Riverside Drive and have an apartment.
So we drove back up there and then went to see the Bonds.
And they...
I said, God, this is terrible what's happening to you all.
It shouldn't happen.
You can do... Let's see, I believe there's a vacancy across the street from 108th.
Number 108th on a big five-story apartment kind of like a townhouse.
And we went over there to see that.
And showed up some gracious people there.
And I was a mason.
I had a Masonic pen on that time.
He said, my God, a fellow mason.
He's a wonderful person.
He says, come here.
The fifth floor is vacant.
Went up there and it was Victor Herbert's.
His composing room was called Corkman.
Said, this is yours.
He wanted it for $50 a month.
It was just a room and a kitchen and a band.
So that's where we stayed.
And set our sales up, I say, because then the real worry started.
There was no money, so we had to go around.
Just pound the pavements.
Catch a C-Tech one side of the street.
Go see all the advertising points and architects and magazines.
And nothing happened until I pulled this little funny story.
trip of mine, everybody knows about it.
That's what you call a chilly episode.
So I decided I had to do something.
You couldn't get where they ought.
I showed them my things, and they said, oh, this is wonderful.
But nope, I got no acceptance.
I think it was just because the market was pretty crowded.
But anyhow, I said, I'm going to do something.
So I got me some Gephardt's chili.
in a stainless can heater and I had this old greasy Stetson hat of mine.
I put it on and I burned some holes in it like bullet holes.
Then I went up to see a magazine called Pencil Points.
The editor was Ken Reed.
And I went to, he came, I came in there and he said, well, God, where you from?
I said, Texas.
Well, where'd you get the bullet holes?
Oh, I don't know.
We had a little run-in down at the bar.
I was working with some, any kind of story.
Then I told him,
And we sat around.
He got interested.
Boy, he was a terrific person.
God, understanding.
And he looked at my work, and he says, my God, you've got something here.
I didn't know anybody from Texas ever did this type of thing.
Pencil drawings, I've been doing all that time.
From Washington, we'd watch all the Carolinas.
But I had a great sheaf of just sketching, sketching.
And he said, well, now it's time for lunch.
Why about us going out somewhere?
I want to give you a nice lunch.
And I says, well, I don't know, but I'm kind of used to eating.
I would have been eating down on the Texas way now, but I have my own brand of vittles, of course.
I've got some with me, I believe.
Chili, I always carry with me.
I got to stay in the heater.
Whenever I can, my wife would stop in the park, just heat up and eat chili.
Oh, you're talking about now, isn't that some damn good thing?
And I went back to the shipping room with them and said, can I have a place?
So they all gathered around.
I hit my stand here and I opened that can of chili and poured it down there.
And they went, ah, let's get one more pepper.
And I believe it.
Well, it's hot enough, yeah.
So we got some paper bowls and plates, whatever.
I carried those with me, too.
And I concocted my chili.
I started eating it.
I said, you want to try it?
They said, oh, come on, try it.
I said, no, Tony, you got to adjust it, Tony.
She said, man, we got to.
We got cast out of Stomachstown, Texas.
So I went there, and I was the first one.
Then they just hooped and hollered at me and said, bye, golly, you come on.
So he took me out to his house, his editor, a pleasant one.
He went and had a bridge digested and printed out there and got my story.
And he ran this beautiful story on me, the pencil boy.
And it opened the door, and it came out to architects.
I got calls from some of the top men, but I said, I'm going to get...
So that's when I started studying under the top delineators called pencil artists in New York.
And they were beautiful to me when they went to me, because I was more or less an eccentric, whatever you want to call it, silly, crazy Texan.
But I had to just always elaborate on everything in real Texas.
I just went after it.
I had some old scrubby boots.
But I've got House Beautiful took me on, Pictorial Review, all these old magazines.
But everything just fell into place beautifully after that.
And I went off and started teaching up at New York University.
And I don't know, I delivered.
said, we got a depression around the corner.
That's just before the depression.
He said, it'd be better if you all went on back to Texas.
That's what Ken Reed told me.
That man was so good to me.
Am I talking loud enough now?
Yeah, it's going fine.
All right.
And so then we got a call from Paul Franke.
He was up here at the time.
He was a cadet colonel and a big shot in the
I started an advertising agency.
There was just two of them.
He got a mentor, and they were handling the Anderson Clayton account.
They had gotten on the road with it, and then they said, by golly, we need an auditor.
And of course, they were very close to me, because he's the one that put me on this first 52 series for Anderson Clayton.
So I said, oh, I want to go home with my wife.
I want to see my family, my brothers.
And we were put alone, just down to Nubbin.
I'd run through everything.
My car wasn't hot.
I couldn't get a dollar.
I had $20 a month extra for my car.
But I picked up enough money to get on the road again.
So we decided, let's go.
Packed up and just like that, we crossed the river and started down.
And how we got to Houston, buddy, I think we came to Houston with 30 cents in our pocket.
But then I went on to see Frankie.
And he said, we can set up for you at the Cotton Exchange building.
Come on.
I'd stay with us a while.
And we'd go on the motor.
So I went and looked it over.
And I had some work for me to do.
And here I go on this.
New Venture, a third partner in the advertising firm.
And things worked.
It was a good deal.
And I got to still do my architectural work and was a partner in the firm.
And I always stayed in a horrible place, but just like you were.
So things got right.
But I don't know, from then on, it just seemed like it was rather, we didn't have any work, you know.
We had just a handful of accounts.
But we finally picked up another here and there, just a little.
Finally got the umbilical cord.
And that was it.
The ultimate.
We worked at that big oil car.
It was handled by a New York firm at that time.
So we got hit and then we were well on the road then.
I handled all the advertising.
I mean, the layouts and the finished art.
It was a work out, and we picked them.
Finally, I ended up with about 20 accounts.
This is in 1930?
This was in 1928 when I came in.
1929, and stayed there.
In 30, we got on the road in the big way.
But that was the fall of 1929 when I came in.
Of course, the bottom did drop.
The depression came.
Everybody, all my friends, just completely wiped out.
That's what it is.
But we had this forewarning about it.
But from then on, of course, I got more involved in the Houston scene and working with art to find the fine arts in the museums.
But it was a haphazard type of thing, I guess.
What do you call it?
All the time, I was out jumping around trying to find answers.
But that's when the firm opened up there with Frankie and Wilkerson.
I stayed with them from then on out.
But it was a hard game, too.
We finally got more accounts.
We got bigger and bigger.
We kind of ended up as second biggest agency in the state of Texas.
But it was a workout.
I didn't know advertising could be that hard.
Because I was art director, I had to get to lay outside and consume ideas.
Creativity, deadlines, deadlines, deadlines.
And that brought on some problems.
We all started that.
But advertising is a killer.
You know, mortality rate in advertising
I don't know whether I should be putting this in there.
Sure, go ahead.
As far as alcoholics are concerned, it's the highest of any profession, because for that reason, that is creativity and deadlines.
And he just had to strain and strain to get something out.
He said, oh, yeah, we get on the road with a good cut.
I call it cut.
But every one of us got pretty much a job, and so did our accounts.
And that went on for a while.
It finally leveled off.
But it was a hazardous experience.
out of the West.
I stayed with the agency, of course.
Then I got more into fine arts and painting.
I started submitting things to shows and museums and shows over the United States.
And I've got some pretty good goals over there.
I've got an international watercolor show.
I've got an international and a national show.
And I finally got more and more absorbed with my painting, back to the painting.
So I started going down to Galveston.
Every spare minute I had was doing watercolors in Galveston.
I thought I'd made one sum about 50, 60 watercolors, and started putting them in shows, and got an entree in that area, which I had aspired to.
But I didn't look for competition.
I just wanted my thing to be seen.
I only got, I think, $25 or $35 for a watercolor then, and $10, $15 for a pencil drawing.
Of course, at the moment, I'm just going to think, I'm just going,
Not sky high, but kind of another plateau.
But that was only the beginning.
But see, all those things, you just trace back your career.
You get going beautifully, and then wham, comes the roadblock, and you get struck down.
One thing after another, it seemed like.
But it was part of it.
I mean, that's why I like that verse.
I don't know why, but some of it.
It kind of shook you.
You get to so darn complacent, and you get a few plaudits in the crowd, and nice reviews, and...
